00:55:01.606 --> 00:55:07.037
They returned with the elephants, giraffes, and other beautiful animals,

00:55:07.037 --> 00:55:09.284
and with gorgeous plants

00:55:09.284 --> 00:55:12.109
And some ambassadors from different states.

00:55:12.109 --> 00:55:17.999
And they left their fleet in the ports of China to rot.

00:55:17.999 --> 00:55:20.108
What did Europe do?

00:55:20.108 --> 00:55:22.574
They discovered Chinese gunpowder

00:55:22.574 --> 00:55:27.098
and they discovered how to make cannons as well.

00:55:27.098 --> 00:55:29.380
And just like that,

00:55:29.380 --> 00:55:32.210
with no time wasted,

00:55:32.210 --> 00:55:37.002
they built the deadliest ships in human history.

00:55:37.002 --> 00:55:39.573
Their ships were relatively small

00:55:39.573 --> 00:55:42.358
and they utilized gun ports

00:55:42.358 --> 00:55:49.021
that have the capability to penetrate a much larger ship and sink it

00:55:49.021 --> 00:55:53.719
So neither Muslims, Chinese, nor anyone else could stop them.

00:55:53.719 --> 00:55:59.186
When Portuguese and Spanish sailed down to the Indian ocean,

00:55:59.186 --> 00:56:01.230
no one could resist them.

00:56:01.230 --> 00:56:03.746
That's why they controlled the Indian Sea.

00:56:03.746 --> 00:56:06.437
The pattern of trade has changed completely.

00:56:06.437 --> 00:56:12.310
The pattern of trade was prevalent between Muslims, Chinese, Indians, and others.

00:56:12.310 --> 00:56:16.405
By the way, most of the customs were according to Shari‘a.

00:56:16.405 --> 00:56:21.467
Even the Chinese followed the law of the sea as dictated by Shari‘a.

00:56:21.467 --> 00:56:24.056
It's not that it's inescapable.

00:56:24.056 --> 00:56:29.661
It is because it existed before and it was customary, so they took it and used it.

00:56:29.661 --> 00:56:32.269
This is all broken now.

00:56:32.269 --> 00:56:36.820
And the Portuguese came and said: If you want to pass, you have to pay us money.

00:56:36.820 --> 00:56:41.347
But if there is gold in your cargo, whether you pay or not, we will take you and your gold.

00:56:41.347 --> 00:56:43.990
You are our captive, and your gold is ours.

00:56:43.990 --> 00:56:47.966
We would build palaces with it in Portugal, France, and England.

00:56:47.966 --> 00:56:50.741
Didn't the Muslims have the same goals?

00:56:50.741 --> 00:56:55.452
They had a desire to expand, and they did so.

00:56:55.452 --> 00:57:01.310
To the point where Harun al-Rashid said to a cloud: Pour it wherever you want, the taxes from that are mine.

00:57:01.310 --> 00:57:05.205
It's true, and this is how occupying other people works, but there are limits.

00:57:05.205 --> 00:57:10.545
If you want, we can discuss why it was like that, specifically after the 17th century.

00:57:10.545 --> 00:57:15.548
Europe was the exception in human history.

00:57:15.548 --> 00:57:18.688
This is what we should understand.

00:57:18.688 --> 00:57:23.220
We have been living as cohesive and political societies

00:57:23.220 --> 00:57:27.088
as small cities or city-states

00:57:27.088 --> 00:57:29.218
for 7000 years.

00:57:29.218 --> 00:57:31.908
Our history today

00:57:31.908 --> 00:57:35.941
or the known written history,

00:57:35.941 --> 00:57:39.740
More or less, we are somewhat aware of it.

00:57:39.740 --> 00:57:42.667
Rather, we know a lot about where it stopped and when.

00:57:42.667 --> 00:57:45.564
It goes back to five or six thousand years ago.

00:57:45.564 --> 00:57:49.108
In human history, this has been written about, and we know it.

00:57:49.108 --> 00:57:53.433
The only exception to this history is Europe.

00:57:53.433 --> 00:57:58.985
If it were to be illustrated on a diagram,

00:57:58.985 --> 00:58:01.643
you begin from the corner

00:58:01.643 --> 00:58:04.897
the line will go smoothly

00:58:04.897 --> 00:58:07.525
barely above the lower line

00:58:07.525 --> 00:58:11.224
and suddenly there will be a jump

00:58:11.224 --> 00:58:14.859
this jump takes about 2% of the line length

00:58:14.859 --> 00:58:19.257
But whether up or down, it depends on how you view European history.

00:58:19.257 --> 00:58:22.450
If you see it as Wael Hallaq did, then it will go down.

00:58:22.450 --> 00:58:28.830
But if you see it according to who sold their souls and minds to the colonization, it will go up.

00:58:28.830 --> 00:58:31.364
Can we know why it went down based on Wael's view?

00:58:31.364 --> 00:58:34.477
Because most people see it go up.

00:58:34.477 --> 00:58:36.991
This episode will have digressions

00:58:36.991 --> 00:58:40.057
and these digressions are fantastic.

00:58:40.057 --> 00:58:41.696
- (We can go back if you want to.)
- Sure.

00:58:41.696 --> 00:58:43.956
Then let's go back to the evolution of Shari‘a.

00:58:43.956 --> 00:58:46.295
Could guide us to how it happened.

00:58:46.295 --> 00:58:47.297
Great.

00:58:47.297 --> 00:58:49.543
Thank you for taking us back.

00:58:49.543 --> 00:58:51.075
No problem.

00:58:51.075 --> 00:59:01.921
I can say that the biggest and most important act

00:59:01.921 --> 00:59:05.445
that happened in the history of Islam to establish Shari‘a

00:59:05.445 --> 00:59:10.173
was in the era of Omar Ibn Al-Khattab, may Allah be pleased with him.

00:59:10.173 --> 00:59:18.458
Omar played a frightening role in the creation of Islam.

00:59:18.458 --> 00:59:19.710
Why is that?

00:59:19.721 --> 00:59:23.050
Of course, he established the Diwans and many other acts.

00:59:23.050 --> 00:59:26.438
But half of the Diwans were originally Persian.

00:59:26.438 --> 00:59:32.830
He utilized them with superb intelligence.

00:59:32.830 --> 00:59:35.996
Of course, this is clear to all.

00:59:35.996 --> 00:59:38.420
But what did he really do?

00:59:38.420 --> 00:59:43.262
Since the beginning, he ordered that wherever there is an Islamic gathering,

00:59:43.262 --> 00:59:47.091
and usually those tribes that participated in the invasion

00:59:47.091 --> 00:59:49.677
were in conflict with each other.

00:59:49.677 --> 00:59:55.731
When they arrived in Iraq and even in Egypt, in Fustat,

00:59:55.731 --> 00:59:59.121
they started to fight with each other.

00:59:59.121 --> 01:00:01.815
They all participated in occupying Egypt,

01:00:01.815 --> 01:00:05.900
but when they were done, they started disagreeing on some matters.

01:00:05.900 --> 01:00:11.178
They brought with them their tribal history from Arabia.

01:00:11.178 --> 01:00:13.153
Disagreements started to happen.

01:00:13.153 --> 01:00:15.121
Omar didn't want that.

01:00:15.121 --> 01:00:17.198
There are other places to conquer.

01:00:17.198 --> 01:00:19.458
There is a state to be established.

01:00:19.458 --> 01:00:21.790
An empire.

01:00:21.790 --> 01:00:23.616
So, what did he do?

01:00:23.616 --> 01:00:28.479
Any place that has an Islamic gathering should have a mosque built immediately.

01:00:28.479 --> 01:00:30.480
What is a mosque?

01:00:30.480 --> 01:00:33.281
We hear and read about it a lot in history.

01:00:33.281 --> 01:00:37.592
They say: He built mosques on the frontiers.

01:00:37.592 --> 01:00:39.672
But what does this really mean?

01:00:39.672 --> 01:00:44.167
The mosque is not just a building.

01:00:44.167 --> 01:00:47.072
The first step to having a mosque is the building.

01:00:47.072 --> 01:00:48.545
A small step.

01:00:48.545 --> 01:00:50.291
However, what happens inside the mosque?

01:00:50.291 --> 01:00:53.127
What are the practices in the mosque?

01:00:53.127 --> 01:00:57.876
The mosque has an Imam and a muezzin.

01:00:57.876 --> 01:01:01.409
Although it was small, the mosque was present.

01:01:01.409 --> 01:01:04.854
They started reciting stories.

01:01:04.854 --> 01:01:09.181
The stories contained a lot of the Prophet's Hadiths

01:01:09.181 --> 01:01:12.732
and many of the Prophet's commands and actions,

01:01:12.732 --> 01:01:16.844
including what he did and didn't do and what he forbade or didn't forbid.

01:01:16.844 --> 01:01:20.593
It included a lot of al-Athar.

01:01:20.593 --> 01:01:29.043
Al-Athar are the sayings and the language that are a kind of source for our actions.

01:01:29.043 --> 01:01:32.830
Or it could be Eibrah (a cautionary lesson or story that serves to warn).

01:01:32.830 --> 01:01:35.768
The Eibrah guides the actions.

01:01:35.768 --> 01:01:38.231
This is why it's called that.

01:01:38.231 --> 01:01:42.524
When he built the mosques,

01:01:42.524 --> 01:01:52.659
and this is 10 to 15 years after the death of the Prophet,

01:01:52.659 --> 01:01:58.068
people started going to the mosque

01:01:58.068 --> 01:02:01.501
Those occupiers who went to the mosques

01:02:01.501 --> 01:02:05.866
their leaders were, without a doubt, Muslims to the fullest.

01:02:05.866 --> 01:02:08.200
They were loyal to the cause.

01:02:08.200 --> 01:02:11.777
While those tribes were apostate a few years ago.

01:02:11.777 --> 01:02:15.733
Abu Bakr, who ruled before Omar, was fighting them.

01:02:15.733 --> 01:02:20.616
They took part in the conquests as well.

01:02:20.616 --> 01:02:25.746
They were only halfway committed to Islam.

01:02:25.746 --> 01:02:31.839
We don't assume that all Muslims who conquered

01:02:31.839 --> 01:02:36.878
 understood Islam perfectly on a personal level.

01:02:36.878 --> 01:02:38.851
Some of them wanted other things.

01:02:38.851 --> 01:02:41.566
However, the majority of them and all the leaders were pure.

01:02:41.566 --> 01:02:43.433
The leadership was pure.

01:02:43.433 --> 01:02:45.553
This is why they conquered.

01:02:45.553 --> 01:02:53.470
That is why 2000 of them can crush 20,000 of their enemies.

01:02:53.470 --> 01:02:57.203
Because they were very committed to the cause.

01:02:57.203 --> 01:03:00.810
And they had children.

01:03:00.810 --> 01:03:03.819
They sent their children to the mosque.

01:03:03.819 --> 01:03:06.800
And this generation, the generation of these children,

01:03:06.800 --> 01:03:12.886
the descendants of those who conquered lands for Islam.

01:03:12.886 --> 01:03:19.057
It is the generation that started to produce people who not only have faith in Islam

01:03:19.057 --> 01:03:27.710
but also have a commitment to what Islam requires as a civilization

01:03:27.710 --> 01:03:31.089
and a personal and social concept.

01:03:31.089 --> 01:03:37.388
Islam is not only about the two Shahada.

01:03:37.388 --> 01:03:41.996
They are not enough to make you a true Muslim.

01:03:41.996 --> 01:03:46.321
They do introduce you to Islam and let you in Islam.

01:03:46.321 --> 01:03:49.451
However, when you enter through the house door,

01:03:49.451 --> 01:03:52.622
you don't stop at the door and call it home.

01:03:52.622 --> 01:03:56.267
You don't put your bed at the house door.

01:03:56.267 --> 01:04:01.110
You have to live long enough in it before it becomes part of you.

01:04:01.110 --> 01:04:06.373
Islam is about forming subjectivity, which is the most important thing.

01:04:06.373 --> 01:04:08.913
My dear friend, we have to understand one thing.

01:04:08.913 --> 01:04:12.882
There is no understanding of any phenomenon today,

01:04:12.882 --> 01:04:17.208
a phenomenon that is related to human formation,

01:04:17.208 --> 01:04:20.850
unless it goes back to self-formation.

01:04:20.850 --> 01:04:26.191
We have to understand who we are and who the rest are.

01:04:26.191 --> 01:04:31.804
Why is your program so successful?

01:04:31.804 --> 01:04:35.584
I've been thinking about it for a few weeks.

01:04:35.584 --> 01:04:41.040
If I take you off your show and put someone else on it,

01:04:41.040 --> 01:04:43.230
The show will change completely. But why?

01:04:43.230 --> 01:04:45.681
Because of your subjectivity.

01:04:45.681 --> 01:04:47.737
The way you think

01:04:47.737 --> 01:04:49.728
The way you ask your guest

01:04:49.728 --> 01:04:51.422
The way you treat your guest

01:04:51.422 --> 01:04:56.485
They bring everything.

01:04:56.485 --> 01:05:02.830
It is hard sometimes to understand what exactly has to do with self-formation.

01:05:02.830 --> 01:05:07.174
But all together, it becomes a tremendous success. All praise to Allah.

01:05:07.174 --> 01:05:12.780
Subjectivity is when someone says: I'm not comfortable with him; I prefer another one.

01:05:12.780 --> 01:05:14.880
But what does it mean, and why?

01:05:14.880 --> 01:05:17.842
You aren't uncomfortable with him for no reason.

01:05:17.842 --> 01:05:20.640
But you are uncomfortable with his subjectivity.

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:22.938
Subjectivity is everything.

01:05:22.938 --> 01:05:25.191
And there was an Islamic subjectivity.

01:05:25.191 --> 01:05:28.031
The tribes that participated in the conquests,

01:05:28.031 --> 01:05:30.556
their subjectivity was not purely Islamic.

01:05:30.556 --> 01:05:35.166
Once the first generation was created and grew up in mosques,

01:05:35.166 --> 01:05:41.206
Islamic subjectivity started to form as if almost everything was there.

01:05:41.206 --> 01:05:46.048
Where did jurisprudence originate?

01:05:46.048 --> 01:05:54.753
This is an undeniable truth that cannot be downgraded below that of the pyramids.

01:05:54.753 --> 01:05:58.214
The pyramids, wonders of Egypt, stand tall and high.

01:05:58.214 --> 01:06:01.137
This is also one of the most important facts.

01:06:01.137 --> 01:06:11.524
This is due to jurisprudence and the law,

01:06:11.524 --> 01:06:15.914
and it was called Shari‘a rather than law, which is what we call it now,

01:06:15.914 --> 01:06:20.840
The Law of the Political Apparatus and the Law of the Social Apparatus,

01:06:20.840 --> 01:06:27.922
they were created entirely by simple members of society, sometimes they were even poor.

01:06:27.922 --> 01:06:36.962
When a judge from Egypt or Damascus was ruling between the people,

01:06:36.962 --> 01:06:39.803
or he was judging the people,

01:06:39.803 --> 01:06:44.509
certain cases were sometimes incomprehensible to him

01:06:44.509 --> 01:06:47.063
So he writes to Omar, for example,.

01:06:47.063 --> 01:06:56.247
He says: I have a difficult problem with a case. Please guide us.

01:06:56.247 --> 01:07:03.844
Omar says in most cases: You should strive to deduce the best opinion (Ijtihad).

01:07:03.844 --> 01:07:08.327
Nowadays, if I didn't know what the law is,

01:07:08.327 --> 01:07:13.574
and I write to the director of a legal office in the state,

01:07:13.574 --> 01:07:17.041
do you think they'll tell me to do ijtihad?

01:07:17.041 --> 01:07:18.464
In this age?

01:07:18.464 --> 01:07:22.226
The state has a law, and it always does.

01:07:22.226 --> 01:07:24.285
The state is the one that sets the law.

01:07:24.285 --> 01:07:28.584
No one can ever challenge that.

01:07:28.584 --> 01:07:31.751
But the Caliph did not legislate.

01:07:31.751 --> 01:07:33.546
Omar, for instance,

01:07:33.546 --> 01:07:36.695
he had legal stances

01:07:36.695 --> 01:07:40.270
because he was a companion and not because he was a caliph

01:07:40.270 --> 01:07:41.919
What's the difference?

01:07:41.919 --> 01:07:45.861
The companion is a jurist.

01:07:45.861 --> 01:07:53.251
He understands how the Prophet would have solved the problem.

01:07:53.251 --> 01:07:56.145
He knows from his experience.

01:07:56.145 --> 01:07:59.181
A companion of the Prophet is a person who was with him.

01:07:59.181 --> 01:08:05.109
The companionship was not only on a social level.

01:08:05.109 --> 01:08:07.522
The social aspect is what comes to mind first.

01:08:07.522 --> 01:08:10.717
In Islam, the issue of Prophet's companions

01:08:10.717 --> 01:08:14.864
is a purely epistemological issue.

01:08:14.864 --> 01:08:19.855
This means the companion knows about what the Prophet wants,

01:08:19.855 --> 01:08:22.654
and the prophet knows what Allah wants,

01:08:22.654 --> 01:08:26.596
in a way that is the closest thing between any human being and another

01:08:26.596 --> 01:08:29.825
or between any human being and any other divine power.

01:08:29.825 --> 01:08:33.108
Omar was a companion.

01:08:33.108 --> 01:08:35.926
Ibn Mas'ud, for example, was even closer than Omar.

01:08:35.926 --> 01:08:42.215
One of the greatest lawmen was Ibn Mas'ud,

01:08:42.215 --> 01:08:45.384
if it were possible to call it that today.

01:08:45.384 --> 01:08:48.125
He is the greatest lawman in the history of Islam.

01:08:48.125 --> 01:08:51.025
How did they come to that?

01:08:51.025 --> 01:08:56.868
They were so close to the prophet that they almost knew what the prophet knew.

01:08:56.868 --> 01:08:59.018
It's a matter of knowing.

01:08:59.018 --> 01:09:02.890
The issue is not that he sat with the Prophet and drank coffee

01:09:02.890 --> 01:09:05.355
and they became friends.

01:09:05.355 --> 01:09:09.251
Omar and Abu Bakr used to go with the prophet and eat breakfast together,

01:09:09.251 --> 01:09:13.929
and they visit even Jewish schools

01:09:13.929 --> 01:09:16.060
and listen to what they teach there.

01:09:16.060 --> 01:09:19.172
They were open to others, and they did a lot of things together.

01:09:19.172 --> 01:09:24.179
But this in itself is not a social relationship; it is an epistemological relationship.

01:09:24.179 --> 01:09:28.857
The new generation that grew up in mosques and the teachings of mosques

01:09:28.857 --> 01:09:31.114
and what was happening in the mosques

01:09:31.114 --> 01:09:33.376
They were the jurists.

01:09:33.376 --> 01:09:36.176
The jurisprudence became in the hands of the people

01:09:36.176 --> 01:09:38.640
and not in the hands of politics.

01:09:38.640 --> 01:09:41.342
And from here, we begin to understand the vast difference

01:09:41.342 --> 01:09:46.529
between the concept of Islamic political structure

01:09:46.529 --> 01:09:50.702
and the Western political structure today.

01:09:50.702 --> 01:09:56.322
For example, if someone had a problem

01:09:56.322 --> 01:10:02.667
and he wants to consult someone,

01:10:02.667 --> 01:10:08.185
he would go to ordinary people who specialize in Jurisprudence.

01:10:08.185 --> 01:10:10.353
You can find other stories like this.

01:10:10.353 --> 01:10:14.377
There was a leather seller

01:10:14.377 --> 01:10:19.110
as you know, like in shoes, clothing, etc.

01:10:19.110 --> 01:10:25.866
In front of his shop in the market, he teaches his students jurisprudence.

01:10:25.866 --> 01:10:29.230
We are talking about approximately the year 80 Hijri.

01:10:29.230 --> 01:10:32.831
They were sitting in a circle around him to learn about jurisprudence.

01:10:32.831 --> 01:10:38.189
And someone interrupted his lesson

01:10:38.189 --> 01:10:41.292
because he wanted to buy a leather belt.

01:10:41.292 --> 01:10:46.373
So the teacher stood up, sold the belt, and took the money,

01:10:46.373 --> 01:10:49.281
and went back to sit with his students to continue his lesson.

01:10:49.281 --> 01:10:51.830
This is in the Medina only, or in all cities?

01:10:51.830 --> 01:10:56.462
This story is either from Basra or Kufa; I can't remember.

01:10:56.462 --> 01:11:04.037
Because they were some of the first centers for the emergence of al-Fiqh (jurisprudence).

01:11:04.037 --> 01:11:07.930
The first formation of jurisprudence has begun.

01:11:07.930 --> 01:11:12.748
It was an answer to the question: What do we do in these cases?

01:11:12.748 --> 01:11:17.809
It came from these people, who are among the social average.

01:11:17.809 --> 01:11:22.161
They were not either military or political leaders.

01:11:22.161 --> 01:11:24.488
People like you and me, as they say.

01:11:24.488 --> 01:11:32.743
Some of them are small traders, or even rich ones in a few instances.

01:11:32.743 --> 01:11:37.221
I mean, they were ordinary people who lived a normal life.

01:11:37.221 --> 01:11:41.202
May I inquire about something?

01:11:41.202 --> 01:11:50.746
This could create a dilemma

01:11:50.746 --> 01:11:57.721
What if someone issued a fatwa that was contrary to what Islam agrees upon?

01:11:57.721 --> 01:12:00.040
Is there someone to correct him?

01:12:00.040 --> 01:12:02.830
It depends.

01:12:02.830 --> 01:12:05.724
Is someone going to stop him and tell him that he is wrong?

01:12:05.724 --> 01:12:09.441
Yes, there were, of course, debates about the opinions.

01:12:09.441 --> 01:12:14.636
I mean, this is a statement, and when one comes out with a statement, then it is just a statement.

01:12:14.636 --> 01:12:18.716
You'll find that Omar bin Al-Khattab appoints the Wali (prefect).

01:12:18.716 --> 01:12:21.030
A wali of Iraq, for example.

01:12:21.030 --> 01:12:22.630
No.

01:12:22.630 --> 01:12:26.210
But he is the one who sent him there.

01:12:26.210 --> 01:12:28.054
- (As a judge?)
- Yes, a judge.

01:12:28.054 --> 01:12:30.510
- (Yes, that correct)
- I, as a representative of the state, appointed him.

01:12:30.510 --> 01:12:34.286
As a ruler and a wali, not as a government.

01:12:34.286 --> 01:12:38.470
A little while ago, you said

01:12:38.470 --> 01:12:41.446
that this happens to simple people.

01:12:41.446 --> 01:12:52.632
But in fact, the leader, Caliph, Commander of the faithful, or whatever, is the one who appointed the wali, or judge.

01:12:52.632 --> 01:12:58.158
I realize that, but what I am talking about is something else entirely.

01:12:58.158 --> 01:13:06.326
Of course, judges are part of the legal system.

01:13:06.326 --> 01:13:11.220
